        <div class="ASM-h3-Subheading clearfix colelem shared_content" id="u79846-4" data-muse-uid="U79846" data-muse-type="txt_frame" data-IBE-flags="txtStyleSrc" data-content-guid="u79846-4_content" style="width:569px;margin-left:0"><!-- content -->
          <h1 id="u79846-2">SUGAR SHACK - THE GREAT FRENCH CANADIAN EXPERIENCE </h1>
       </div>   
       <div class="clearfix colelem" id="pu79797-13"><!-- group -->

        </div>
        <!-- /m_editable -->
        <div class="ASM---p---body-text clearfix grpelem shared_content left-block-1" id="u79797-13" data-muse-uid="U79797" data-muse-type="txt_frame" data-ibe-flags="txtStyleSrc" data-content-guid="u79797-13_content"><!-- content -->
         <p id="u79797-2">One of the activities most enjoyed by visitors is the Quebecoise "Cabane à Sucre", or "sugaring-off" party, a festive, informal event, unique to Québec which builds on their legendary "joie de vivre". Similar to harvesting festivals in other countries, this traditional celebration has its roots in the French Canadian culture and the pioneer festivities that heralded the slow end of the harsh winters and the return of spring. An annual ritual to this day for French Canadian Quebecers, a colorful re-creation of this tradition will be experienced on this memorable tour. </p>
         <p id="u79797-3">&nbsp;</p>
         <p id="u79797-5">Only 45 minutes from Montréal, La Sucrerie de la Montagne is located in the wooded setting of Mont-Rigaud. En route, your guide aboard your private coach will provide brief commentaries on points of interest en route to Sucrerie de la Montagne, including a short history of the Indian legends regarding maple syrup and a description on how and why Cabane à Sucre events came to be in Québec, providing a historical and cultural context.</p>
         <p id="u79797-6">&nbsp;</p>
         <p id="u79797-8">Upon arrival, you will discover a real sugaring off party with your amazing pioneer hosts dressed in period costumes. A glass of Wapiti in hand, you’ll be taken on a short tour of the buildings, learn how maple syrup is made and visit the bakery. Your journey will continue inside, where you will be invited to gather around for traditional storytelling, as passed down in the manner of the host's ancestors. An authentic Quebecoise lunch is served in a traditional setting. After lunch, you will be invited back outside, where an axe throwing demonstration will take place. You are sure to enjoy a truly authentic French Canadian experience.</p>
         <p id="u79797-9">&nbsp;</p>
         <p id="u79797-11">Duration of tour, including lunch: 4.5 hours </p>


